                    <comment id="13029955" author="stefan@jira" created="Fri, 6 May 2011 15:36:43 +0100"  >regression of &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/JCR-2762&quot; title=&quot;Optimize bundle serialization&quot;&gt;&lt;strike&gt;JCR-2762&lt;/strike&gt;&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
test case: &lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
any long value &amp;gt; 0x3FFFFFFFFFFFFFFF (i.e. with any of the 2 most significant bits set)&lt;br/&gt;
causes an overflow on deserialization.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
this obviously also includes Long.MAX_VALUE and Long.MIN_VALUE...&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
example:&lt;br/&gt;
long test = 0x3FFFFFFFFFFFFFFFL;&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&lt;br/&gt;
BundleWriter.writeVarLong(test);&lt;br/&gt;
test == BundleReader.readVarLong()  // =&amp;gt; ok&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
test++;&lt;br/&gt;
BundleWriter.writeVarLong(test);&lt;br/&gt;
=&amp;gt; BundleReader.readVarLong() returns 0</comment>
                    <comment id="13030033" author="jukkaz" created="Fri, 6 May 2011 18:13:11 +0100"  >Ouch, good catch! Fixed in revision 1100286 along with tests also for some other value types.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
Luckily this is not a serialization bug so none of the stored data itself is compromized unless used as input for copies or further calculations. However, we&amp;#39;ll need to backport this fix to the 2.2 branch and warn people not to rely on large values read from the repository until this fix has been applied. I&amp;#39;ll take care of that first thing next week.</comment>
                    <comment id="13038564" author="jukkaz" created="Tue, 24 May 2011 14:57:34 +0100"  >Merged to the 2.2 branch in revision 1127054.</comment>
